Objectdays 2000 in Erfurt , Germany October 9 - 12 , 2000 Today , many companies are making an expensive shift to object technology . Currently Java is evolving from a programming language to a development platform consisting of Java SDK , Java Swing , JavaBeans , EJB , JNDI , JMS , JSP , JDBC , SQLJ , JTA etc . Obviously real-world objects can easily be modelled in a Java program or applet . However , little is known about what experiences users have in combining Java and databases , for example : - Which progress is made regarding development ? - Which progress is made regarding maintenance ? - Which new problems have to be considered ? These questions are particularly important , since Java technology like many new technologies can result in changes in the way things "get done". Furthermore , companies are acting globally and need wide distributed applications with stable and efficient data stores to provide "just-in-time" information via an intranet or extranet . Java technology becomes the standard platform for such distributed / intranet / extranet applications . This workshop aims to bring together academics , users and practitioners . The goal is to discuss some of the issues and problems that they have experienced , what solutions they have developed and what lessons they have learned . The workshop will be divided into four sessions , three of which will be reserved for participant presentations and one for a panel discussion at the end of the day . Topics of interest include , but are not limited to : - ORDBs ( DB 2 , Informix , Oracle ) - Java to relational mapping tools - JDBC - SQLJ - OODBs ( GemStone , Jasmine , Objectivity / DB , ObjectStore , Poet , VERSANT ) - Java binding of the ODMG standard - Schema evolution - Rapid prototyping - Database access in multi-tier applications - Coexistence with legacy applications - Migration of legacy applications - Case studies - Product comparisons / evaluations - Performance studies - Benchmarks Submission Guidelines : - Research Papers : ( max . 10 pages ) - Experience Reports : ( from 4 to max . 10 pages ) Research contributions are expected to assess the proposed approach with respect to its practical relevance , while industrial papers should highlight open problems and resulting challenges for research . The workshop language is English . Accepted contributions will be published in proceedings in printed and electronic ( CD-ROM ) form . We intend to invite authors of excellent submissions to provide a possibly extended version of their work ( in English ) for a book published by a major publishing company .
